<p><b>Babylon</b> was a <a href="/wiki/City-state" title="City-state">city-state</a> of ancient <a href="/wiki/Mesopotamia" title="Mesopotamia">Mesopotamia</a>, sometimes considered an <a href="/wiki/Empire" title="Empire">empire</a>, the remains of which can be found in present-day <a href="/wiki/Al_Hillah" title="Al Hillah">Al Hillah</a>, <a href="/wiki/Babil_Governorate" title="Babil Governorate">Babil Province</a>, <a href="/wiki/Iraq" title="Iraq">Iraq</a>, about 85 kilometers (55&#160;mi) south of <a href="/wiki/Baghdad" title="Baghdad">Baghdad</a>. All that remains of the original ancient famed city of Babylon today is a mound, or <a href="/wiki/Tell" title="Tell">tell</a>, of broken mud-brick buildings and debris in the fertile Mesopotamian plain between the <a href="/wiki/Tigris" title="Tigris">Tigris</a> and <a href="/wiki/Euphrates" title="Euphrates">Euphrates</a> rivers, in Iraq. Although it has been reconstructed. Historical resources inform us that Babylon was at first a small town, that had sprung up by the beginning of the third millennium <a href="/wiki/BCE" title="BCE" class="mw-redirect">BCE</a> (the dawn of the dynasties). The town flourished and attained prominence and political repute with the rise of the first Babylonian dynasty. It was the "holy city" of <a href="/wiki/Babylonia" title="Babylonia">Babylonia</a> by approximately 2300 BCE, and the seat of the <a href="/wiki/Neo-Babylonian_Empire" title="Neo-Babylonian Empire">Neo-Babylonian Empire</a> from 612 BCE. The <a href="/wiki/Hanging_Gardens_of_Babylon" title="Hanging Gardens of Babylon">Hanging Gardens of Babylon</a> were one of the <a href="/wiki/Seven_Wonders_of_the_Ancient_World" title="Seven Wonders of the Ancient World">Seven Wonders of the Ancient World</a>.</p>
<p>The form <i>Babylon</i> is the Greek variant of <a href="/wiki/Akkadian_language" title="Akkadian language">Akkadian</a> <b>Babilu</b> (<i>bāb-<a href="/wiki/Ilah" title="Ilah">ilû</a></i>, meaning "Gateway of the god(s)", translating <a href="/wiki/Sumerian_language" title="Sumerian language">Sumerian</a> <b>Ka.<a href="/wiki/Dingir" title="Dingir">dingir</a>.ra</b>). In the <a href="/wiki/Hebrew_Bible" title="Hebrew Bible">Hebrew Bible</a>, the name appears as <i>בבל</i> (<i><a href="/wiki/Babel" title="Babel">Babel</a>),</i> interpreted by <i><a href="/wiki/Book_of_Genesis" title="Book of Genesis">Book of Genesis</a></i> 11:9 to mean "confusion" (of languages), from the verb <i>balbal</i>, "to confuse".</p>
